13,IssuesEvent,2016-05-10 19:57:37+00:00,8387179,uiri/toml,364765,uiri,,,closed,Parsing datetime objects doesn't parse their timezone,[],[],0,"# Setup

``` toml
[section]
date = 2016-02-24T13:05:09Z
```

Note the Z on the end: it's saying that this datetime is in Zulu time, or UTC.

# Observed behavior

``` python
>>> with open('test.toml', 'r') as fp:
...     data = toml.loads(fp.read())
... 
>>> data['section']['date']
datetime.datetime(2016, 2, 24, 13, 5, 9)
```

# Expected behavior

``` python
>>> data['section']['date']
datetime.datetime(2016, 2, 24, 13, 5, 9, tzinfo=<UTC>)
```

Per the [TOML spec](https://github.com/toml-lang/toml#user-content-datetime), it would be fine to return naive objects if no TZ were specified, but in the case that the TZ is in fact specified, I'd like to receive a TZ-aware object.",{},{}
15,IssuesEvent,2017-06-18 20:17:19+00:00,8387179,uiri/toml,364765,uiri,,,closed,datetimes are serialized incorrectly,[],[],0,"Hi there, I can't use uiri/toml implementation because of this deal-breaker:

```
>>> from datetime import datetime
>>> tz = pytz.timezone('America/Chicago')
>>> dt_naive = datetime(2017, 6, 6, 12, 34, 56)
>>> dt_aware = tz.localize(dt_naive)
>>> d = {'dt': dt_aware}
>>> print(dt_aware)
2017-06-06 12:34:56-05:00
```

So, I have non-naive datetime in the data.  

```
>>> import toml
>>> toml.dumps(d)
'dt = 2017-06-06T12:34:56Z\n'
                         ^
                         |
                       UTC?!
```

The Z here indicates Zulu time; the serialized datetime is indicated as UTC.  Outputting a naive datetime would perhaps be understandable, but indicating an _incorrect_ timezone is really bad.  

Other libraries don't make this mistake:

```
>>> import pytoml
>>> pytoml.dumps(d)
'dt = 2017-06-06T12:34:56-5.00.0\n'
>>> import yaml
>>> yaml.dump(d)
""{dt: !!timestamp '2017-06-06 12:34:56-05:00'}\n""
```",{},{}
