2042,IssuesEvent,2017-04-09 10:20:38+00:00,29613985,jorgebastida/awslogs,635911,vlcinsky,,,opened,"""no stream match your pattern"" shall not terminate the program with `--watch`",[],[],0,"I have two streams producing continually log records into the same log group. Each produce about 11 records a second.

Getting all log records (without specifying stream name) works well:
```
$ awslogs get /log/group --watch
<log records are flowing reporting streams `stream_alfa` and `stream_beta`>
```

Asking for specific stream terminates:
```
$ awslogs get /log/group stream_alfa --watch
No streams match your pattern 'stream_alfa'
```
# What is wrong
There are two issues:
- apparently existing and live streams are reported as missing when using stream name search parameter
- with `--watch`, even the fact a stream does not exist shall not terminate the program, as it may appear at any moment

# Proposed solution
- with `--watch`, never terminate the program even if the stream seems to be initially missing
- when testing and reporting existence of a stream
  - either test stream existence in whole history (and do not scope the search to some time range)
  - or reword the message to ""no stream match your pattern for currently used time range""",{},{}
