2289,IssuesEvent,2017-02-15 15:38:54+00:00,58594760,johnwheeler/flask-ask,2979205,niallrobinson,,,closed,Idea for robust dialogues,[],[],1,"Hi Flask Ask!

I wrote a python repo (https://github.com/met-office-lab/conversation-skill) for Alexa dialogues a while back which has functionality for robust dialogues, and I wondered if Flask Ask over-takes this, or if I could possibly spin up a PR for flask ask?

The idea is that, for a given intent, the slots have their own prompts, help etc attached to them. So if you trigger an intent with 3 slots say, but you only provide information for one slot, then it walks over the missing slots, robustly asking (with context sensitive help etc) until all the slots are satisfied, then it triggers the original intent.

e.g.
Me: ""What time's the next bus from Exeter to Plymouth?""
Alexa: ""14:20""

but the same code will also do

Me: "" What time's the next bus?""
Alexa: ""Where are you?""
Me: ""What do you mean?""
Alexa: ""I mean where are you starting your journey?""
Me: ""Exeter""
Alexa: ""Where are you going""
Me: ""Plymouth""
Alexa: ""14:20""",{},{}
2294,IssuesEvent,2015-07-08 14:35:30+00:00,8084050,lebedov/msgpack-numpy,3101557,mehdisadeghi,,,opened,msgpack._packer issue,[],[],0,"This is similar to issue #6.

`_packer` is an internal variable of msgpack and if cython is not available when installing msgpack, then it would not be available as well. In this case msgpack will fallback to pure python installation and will not compile its cython extensions.

Does msgpack_numpy explicitly requires those cython extensions to function properly? If yes, then it is a good idea to mention it in documents to inform users about it.

",{},{}
2296,IssuesEvent,2015-06-11 05:15:48+00:00,4053456,martinblech/xmltodict,2148960,1kko,,,opened,postprocessor doesn't have effect on attributes?,[],[],0,"It seems like postprocessor doesn't run on attributes.

```
>>> def postprocessor(path, key, value):
...	try:
...		return key, int(value)
...	except (ValueError, TypeError):
...		return key, value
>>> doc=""""""<mydoc has=""an attribute"" version=2><and><many>elements</many><many>more elements</many><numbers>2</numbers></and></mydoc>""""""
>>> json.dumps(xmltodict.parse(doc))
'{""mydoc"": {""@has"": ""an attribute"", ""@version"": ""2"", ""and"": {""many"": [""elements"", ""more elements""], ""numbers"": ""2""}}}'
>>> json.dumps(xmltodict.parse(doc, postprocessor=postprocessor))
'{""mydoc"": {""@has"": ""an attribute"", ""@version"": ""2"", ""and"": {""many"": [""elements"", ""more elements""], ""numbers"": 2}}}'

```

As of here, `@version` should be converted integer but didn't, while `numbers` converted as integer 2.

Is there other method to run postprocessor on attributes?",{},{}
