4086,IssuesEvent,2016-03-01 17:58:15+00:00,24774658,boto/boto3,4605355,kyleknap,327752,boto,closed,Cannot Import ServiceUnavailableException,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/boto/boto3/labels/duplicate', 'name': 'duplicate', 'color': 'cccccc'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/boto/boto3/labels/feature-request', 'name': 'feature-request', 'color': 'fad8c7'}]",[],3,"Hello,

I'm trying to use boto3 to work with AWS firehose.  As per the boto3 [docs on the AWS firehose method `put_record()`](https://boto3.readthedocs.org/en/latest/reference/services/firehose.html#Firehose.Client.put_record), my code should be prepared to catch `ServiceUnavailableException`:

> If the PutRecord operation throws a ServiceUnavailableException , back off and retry. If the exception persists, it is possible that the throughput limits have been exceeded for the delivery stream.

I cannot find where `ServiceUnavialableException` is defined.  It certainly is not in `boto3` or `botocore`...
```
In [31]: from boto3.exceptions import ServiceUnavailableException
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ImportError                               Traceback (most recent call last)
<ipython-input-31-d0ffff8323fb> in <module>()
----> 1 from boto3.exceptions import ServiceUnavailableException

ImportError: cannot import name ServiceUnavailableException

In [32]: from botocore.exceptions import ServiceUnavailableException
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ImportError                               Traceback (most recent call last)
<ipython-input-32-47b3b14f7ff7> in <module>()
----> 1 from botocore.exceptions import ServiceUnavailableException

ImportError: cannot import name ServiceUnavailableException
```

A `ServiceUnavialableException` does appear to de defined in `boto` though (`from boto.logs.exceptions import ServiceUnavailableException`).  Surely `boto's` version of the exception is not what I'm expected to use?",{},{}
4091,IssuesEvent,2017-07-21 23:29:03+00:00,6670942,boto/botocore,2643092,JordonPhillips,327752,boto,closed,Documentation that contains hyperlinks with different URLs but the same description text all render as the same URL,"[{'id': 225835328, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/boto/botocore/labels/documentation', 'name': 'documentation', 'color': 'c7def8', 'default': False}]",[],1,"Despite the fact that the service definitions (for example the [SES service definition](https://github.com/boto/botocore/blob/develop/botocore/data/ses/2010-12-01/service-2.json)) contain documentation strings with links where the link name is the same and the URLs are different, those documentation strings render through Sphinx all with the same URL.

Here's an example

In the [SES service definition](https://github.com/boto/botocore/blob/develop/botocore/data/ses/2010-12-01/service-2.json), the [documentation string for the `CloneReceiptRuleSet` method](https://github.com/boto/botocore/blob/0d5aa67fa8e2b38312aa3b87f0783a47c2a4d274/botocore/data/ses/2010-12-01/service-2.json#L30) contains this content

```
""<p>Creates a receipt rule set by cloning an existing one. All receipt rules and configurations are copied to the new receipt rule set and are completely independent of the source rule set.</p> <p>For information about setting up rule sets, see the <a href=\""http://docs.aws.amazon.com/ses/latest/DeveloperGuide/receiving-email-receipt-rule-set.html\"">Amazon SES Developer Guide</a>.</p> <p>This action is throttled at one request per second.</p>""
```

Where the link for `Amazon SES Developer Guide` points to the url http://docs.aws.amazon.com/ses/latest/DeveloperGuide/receiving-email-receipt-rule-set.html

However, when you go and look at the [Sphinx rendered documentation](http://boto3.readthedocs.org/en/latest/reference/services/ses.html#SES.Client.clone_receipt_rule_set) for the `CloneReceiptRuleSet` method, the resulting link doesn't point to http://docs.aws.amazon.com/ses/latest/DeveloperGuide/receiving-email-receipt-rule-set.html but instead to http://docs.aws.amazon.com/ses/latest/DeveloperGuide/easy-dkim-dns-records.html

All links on the page that have a link name of `Amazon SES Developer Guide` point to http://docs.aws.amazon.com/ses/latest/DeveloperGuide/easy-dkim-dns-records.html despite the fact that throughout the documentation strings in the service definition, the `Amazon SES Developer Guide` links point to many different URLs.
",{},{}
4107,IssuesEvent,2015-09-18 18:27:59+00:00,6670942,boto/botocore,368057,jamesls,327752,boto,closed,S3 Expires attribute fails when passed a datetime,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/boto/botocore/labels/closing-soon-if-no-response', 'name': 'closing-soon-if-no-response', 'color': '5319e7'}]",[],3,"First, the documentation: Expires (datetime) -- The date and time at which the object is no longer cacheable.

If you set Expires=datetime.datetime.now() (or any datetime object) it fails with an AttributeError.

For example:

import boto3
import datetime

YOUR_BUCKET_HERE = """"
TEST_FILENAME = """"
s3 = boto3.resource('s3')
expire_time = datetime.datetime.now() + datetime.timedelta(minutes=5)
s3.Object(YOUR_BUCKET_HERE, TEST_FILENAME).put(Body=open(TEST_FILENAME, 'rb'), Expires=expire_time)

Fails with an AttributeError, specifically from lib/python3.4/site-packages/botocore/utils.py"", line 318, in parse_timestamp (should have a check to see if the value is already a datetime object and return if it is instead of trying to parse it again).

Giving it an int/float timestamp works, but it still doesn't set an actual expire time on S3. I am not sure if this is related to the original bug.",{},{}
4111,IssuesEvent,2016-09-13 15:16:13+00:00,49535299,boto/s3transfer,464726,millerdev,327752,boto,opened,Reading entire file into memory vs using lock to share file among threads,[],[],0,"I recently upgraded to boto3 v1.4.0 from v1.2.3. The new version now uses `s3transfer` to support uploads, and boto3 `Bucket` objects now provide a method `upload_fileobj` for uploading files, which is very nice. The `upload_fileobj` method delegates to `s3transfer`. However, it appears that s3transfer [reads the entire file into memory](https://github.com/boto/s3transfer/blob/develop/s3transfer/upload.py#L318-L331) when chunking very large files, which has the potential to exhaust RAM. Would it make sense to [use a lock to allow multiple threads to access the fileobj](https://github.com/dimagi/commcare-hq/blob/1bd0a74/corehq/blobs/s3db.py#L166-L282) instead?

Feel free to reuse the code from that final link. I wrote it and would be happy to have it used here.",{},{}
