6219,IssuesEvent,2017-09-07 20:21:56+00:00,91020334,ni/nimi-python,8085768,marcoskirsch,5598284,ni,closed,Move metadata processing to build module,"[{'id': 656402513, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ni/nimi-python/labels/build', 'name': 'build', 'color': 'c2e0c6', 'default': False}, {'id': 603245017, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ni/nimi-python/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}]",[],0,"Right now, each Mako template is responsible for taking the raw metadata as found in source and processing it (merging with add-on metadata, adding missing defaults by calling helper.py functions, etc).

We should improve this. Have all Mako templates receive the metadata fully processed and ready to be consumed. This means some templates will receive more metadata than they need, but the performance/memory hit is not important because it happens during code generation.

Move all the metadata processing functions out of helper.py into its own file (metadata.py? metadata_processing.py?). 

Add unit tests for these functions.",{},{}
6241,IssuesEvent,2015-10-29 17:38:39+00:00,2113510,crossbario/autobahn-python,7746352,icefo,5656948,crossbario,opened,Allow to pass parameters to the called class with the ApplicationRunner.run() method,[],[],0,"I had to pass parameters to a class that is launched by the ApplicationRunner.run() method.

```python
    def run(self, make, args=(), kwargs={}):
        """"""
        Run the application component.

        :param make: A factory that produces instances of :class:`autobahn.asyncio.wamp.ApplicationSession`
           when called with an instance of :class:`autobahn.wamp.types.ComponentConfig`.
        :type make: callable
        """"""
        # 1) factory for use ApplicationSession
        def create():
            cfg = ComponentConfig(self.realm, self.extra)
            try:
                session = make(cfg, *args, **kwargs)
            except Exception:
                # the app component could not be created .. fatal
                print_exc()
                asyncio.get_event_loop().stop()
            else:
                session.debug_app = self.debug_app
                return session

        isSecure, host, port, resource, path, params = parseWsUrl(self.url)

        # 2) create a WAMP-over-WebSocket transport client factory
        transport_factory = WampWebSocketClientFactory(create, url=self.url, serializers=self.serializers,
                                                       debug=self.debug, debug_wamp=self.debug_wamp)

        # 3) start the client
        loop = asyncio.get_event_loop()
        coro = loop.create_connection(transport_factory, host, port, ssl=isSecure)
        loop.run_until_complete(coro)

        # 4) now enter the asyncio event loop
        loop.run_forever()
        loop.close()
```
It's simple but useful in some cases.

Totally unrelated but I think you should add this in your examples:
```python
class MyComponent(ApplicationSession):
    def __init__(self, config=None):
        ApplicationSession.__init__(self, config)
```
because I took me some time to figure out when I tried to extend the examples.

Related this time, I changed the
```python
try:
    session = make(cfg, *args, **kwargs)
except Exception as e:
    # the app component could not be created .. fatal
    print(e)
    asyncio.get_event_loop().stop()
```
in
```python
from traceback import print_exc
try:
    session = make(cfg, *args, **kwargs)
except Exception:
    # the app component could not be created .. fatal
    print_exc()
    asyncio.get_event_loop().stop()
```
because it changes error like this:
```python
__init__() takes 1 positional argument but 2 were given
```
in
```python
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""/usr/local/lib/python3.4/dist-packages/autobahn/asyncio/wamp.py"", line 185, in create
    session = make(cfg, *args, **kwargs)
TypeError: __init__() takes 1 positional argument but 2 were given
```
It doesn't change much for an experienced developer but for a novice/medium like me it means less time trying to figure out why it doesn't work.

