7719,IssuesEvent,2015-07-10 14:52:24+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,13275008,GuillaumeLangelier,11668813,Z3Prover,opened,Crash on using floating point and real transformation (version Win-64 bits 4.4.0),[],[],0,"The following smt2 code makes the last stable binary release (4.4.0) crash on windows 64 bits.

	(declare-const x Real)
	(declare-const y Real)
	(declare-const res Real)

	(define-fun NonLinProd( (num1 Real) (num2 Real) (result Real) ) Bool
		(and
			(fp.eq 
				((_ to_fp 11 53) roundTowardZero result) 
				(fp.mul roundTowardZero 
					((_ to_fp 11 53) roundTowardZero num1) 
					((_ to_fp 11 53) roundTowardZero num2)))
		)	
	)
	;(assert (= res 25))
	(assert (NonLinProd x y res))
	(check-sat)
	;(get-model)

Actually, if result and res are floating point numbers of the good type, it also crashes. If everything (num1, num2, x, y) is floating point, then it works fine.

While I am here, I might as well ask some question that are related to this piece of code. As you can see, I was playing with the translation between reals and floating point. 

* In the API documentation and in some StackOverflow answers, the following warning is mentioned concerning the function “to_real”. However, there is no similar warning for the function “to_fp”. Is the warning also true for “to_fp”?

>  Note that this type of conversion will often result in non-linear constraints over real terms.

* Depending on your answer from the first question, wouldn’t the code shown here be able to mix together reals and floating points without non-linear constraints?

* Does z3 support a fixed point precision numbers as opposed to floating point numbers or do you have any plans to introduce them? The exponent being a constant in this case would probably eliminate non-linear constraints. This kind of precision would be “good enough” for my needs and probably for many problems as well.  

",{},{}
7723,IssuesEvent,2018-07-06 09:05:58+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,18348654,pjljvandelaar,11668813,Z3Prover,opened,Side effects: can they be removed?,[],[],0,"We use problem solvers to handle constraints our users add in their test models.
On top of that we add randomization since in tests we want to vary the input as much as possible.

We however noticed that some numbers are hardly chosen. Why? 
Before trying to randomize we ask the problem solver: does a solution exists with another value?
Since if another solution does not exists, trying to find a random solution is a waste of time.

Based on our experience I generated the follow smt2 input that show two issues we experienced:
```
(get-info :name)
(get-info :version)
(set-option :produce-models true)
(set-logic ALL)
(set-info :smt-lib-version 2.5)

(define-fun
    f1044$validInt ( (x$$1045 Int) ) Bool
    (and (<= 0 x$$1045) (<= 0 (+ 10 (- x$$1045))))
)
(push 1)
(declare-fun $In$1050$0$1$() Int)
(assert (f1044$validInt $In$1050$0$1$))
(check-sat)
(get-value ($In$1050$0$1$))

(push 1)
(assert (and (not (<= 0 (+ (- 2) (- $In$1050$0$1$)))) (<= 0 (+ 4 (- $In$1050$0$1$)))))
(check-sat)
(get-value ($In$1050$0$1$))
(pop 1)

(push 1)
(assert (not (= 0 $In$1050$0$1$)))
(check-sat)
(pop 1)

(push 1)
(assert (and (not (<= 0 (+ (- 2) (- $In$1050$0$1$)))) (<= 0 (+ 4 (- $In$1050$0$1$)))))
(check-sat)
(get-value ($In$1050$0$1$))
(pop 1)

(push 1)
(assert (and (not (<= 0 (+ (- 2) (- $In$1050$0$1$)))) (<= $In$1050$0$1$ 0)))
(check-sat)
(get-value ($In$1050$0$1$))
(pop 1)
(pop 1)
```

And we get the answers:
```
C:\experiments> z3 .\distributionPushPop.smt2
(:name ""Z3"")
(:version ""4.8.0 - build hashcode a12af4a619a0"")
sat
(($In$1050$0$1$ 0))
sat
(($In$1050$0$1$ 0))
sat
sat
(($In$1050$0$1$ 1))
sat
(($In$1050$0$1$ 0))
```

In other words:
```
(push 1)
(assert (not (= 0 $In$1050$0$1$)))
(check-sat)
(pop 1)
```
has a side effect on the later statement (yet since it is popped we had not expected this!)

Although the answer is correct, and no bug is present (see the last test that 0 is indeed also valid),
we wonder whether it is possible to remove this undesired side effect?

For your information: this behavior is also observed in cvc4. However, Yices does exhibit the desired behavior so it seems possible.

Furthermore, we experienced that out commenting the first push (and last pop) results in:
```
 C:\experiments> z3 .\distributionPushPop.smt2
(:name ""Z3"")
(:version ""4.8.0 - build hashcode a12af4a619a0"")
sat
(($In$1050$0$1$ 10))
sat
(($In$1050$0$1$ 0))
sat
sat
(($In$1050$0$1$ 1))
sat
(($In$1050$0$1$ 0)) 
```
Also here we had not expected any effect of encapsulating our statements in a push/pop environment.
We are aware that the answer is correct, but we are surprise that seemingly unrelated statements can cause a change in the given answer.
Both Yices and CVC4 do not show this behavior. So our question: can the side effect of inserting statements with a push/pop environment be removed from Z3?
",{},{}
7729,IssuesEvent,2015-05-30 13:59:04+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,10155819,wintersteiger,11668813,Z3Prover,closed,fp - possible bug around conversions?,[],[],1,"[I think this one is quite similar to #77, which is already fixed but perhaps there're still some issues. I've tried to simplify the benchmarks below, but generated code makes it hard to get good test cases..]

I've two benchmarks, which are almost identical. Here's the first one:

```
(set-option :produce-models true)
(set-logic QF_FPBV)
(define-fun s10 () (_ BitVec 32) #x00000000)
(define-fun s2 () (_ FloatingPoint  8 24) ((_ to_fp 8 24) roundNearestTiesToEven (/ 4419341 8388608)))
(declare-fun s0 () (_ FloatingPoint  8 24))
(declare-fun s1 () (_ BitVec 32))
(assert
   (let ((s3 (fp.eq s0 s2)))
   (let ((s5 (fp.isInfinite s2)))
   (let ((s7 (not s5)))
   (let ((s9 ((_ fp.to_sbv 32) roundNearestTiesToEven s2)))
   (let ((s11 (ite s7 s9 s10)))
   (let ((s12 (= (bvcomp s1 s11) #b1)))
   (let ((s13 (and s3 s12)))
   s13))))))))
(check-sat)
(get-value (s1))
```

Here's the second one:

```
(set-option :produce-models true)
(set-logic QF_FPBV)
(define-fun s10 () (_ BitVec 32) #x00000000)
(define-fun s2 () (_ FloatingPoint  8 24) ((_ to_fp 8 24) roundNearestTiesToEven (/ 4419341 8388608)))
(declare-fun s0 () (_ FloatingPoint  8 24))
(declare-fun s1 () (_ BitVec 32))
(assert
   (let ((s3 (fp.eq s0 s2)))
   (let ((s5 (fp.isInfinite s0)))
   (let ((s7 (not s5)))
   (let ((s9 ((_ fp.to_sbv 32) roundNearestTiesToEven s0)))
   (let ((s11 (ite s7 s9 s10)))
   (let ((s12 (= (bvcomp s1 s11) #b1)))
   (let ((s13 (and s3 s12)))
   s13))))))))
(check-sat)
(get-value (s1))
```
For the first one, z3 says:

```
sat
((s1 #x00000001))
```

For the second, I get:

```
sat
((s1 #x00000000))
```

I do believe both of these benchmarks are essentially equivalent, and the `((s1 #x00000001))` model is the correct answer, while the `((s1 #x00000000))` answer satisfies neither.

Note that the difference between these benchmarks is simply the use of the variable `s0` and `s2` in the conversion and the call to `fp.Infinite`. And there's an explicit requirement in each that `s0` and `s2` must be the same floating-point value (see the boolean `s3`), which is the constant `0.5268265`, i.e., `(/ 4419341 8388608)`

The problem is essentially converting this value to a signed-32-bit vector, and I expect the result to be `1` with the `RNE` rounding mode. So, both benchmarks should produce `1`.",{},{}
