8066,IssuesEvent,2016-08-26 10:07:06+00:00,31315021,Kinto/kinto,546692,leplatrem,13413813,Kinto,opened,Accounts API,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Kinto/kinto/labels/plugin-idea', 'name': 'plugin-idea', 'color': 'eb6420'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Kinto/kinto/labels/question', 'name': 'question', 'color': 'cc317c'}]",[],0,"The current approach with Basic Auth has very strong limitations. Mainly:
* It is hard to refresh the token (aka password) (every object permissions have to be modified before doing it)
* It is hard (if not impossible) to avoid users loosing their permissions [when rotating the hmac](https://github.com/Kinto/kinto/issues/691)

I propose that we make a simplistic plugin that will: 
* Add a new CRUD resource (`/users`) where only the `create` permission is given
* The schema will be `id` (email regex, readonly), `password` (PBKDF2, bcrypt or whatever) and additional metadata
* The record id would be forced to what is provided in basic auth header as user value
* Provide an `account` authentication policy based using basic auth that will lookup in storage backend

When defining permissions on object it could just be `account:robert@patulacci.fr`.

To control who is allowed to create users, we would rely on the setting `kinto.account_create_principals` (like for buckets). When reaching the list of accounts, they would only their own record. Since they created the record, they would be allowed to modify and delete it.

We could deprecated the usage of the current basic auth.

I believe it would make authentication a bit more intuitive in Kinto, and would still be very easy to get started or deploy.

What do you think ?",{},{}
