8649,IssuesEvent,2018-07-18 11:46:10+00:00,16865424,pimutils/vdirsyncer,837573,untitaker,17852924,pimutils,closed,Thanks to the wonders of vdirsync: Floating events.,[],[],3,"As an old DateBk5 user (Pimlico, Palm Pilot) I was used to, and loved, floating events.

A floating event is a basically an ordinary event that is scheduled on a specific date(time). When the event time is passed, the event moves to the next day. So it is 'stuck' on today's date until it is deactivated (checked off).

Using vdirsync this turned out to be very easy to implement. In the vdir, all events are in separate .ics files, and bunches of files are easy to examine and process. So I use a special marker (a hook arrow, ↪) in front of the event summary to designate it as a floating event. A nightly cron task investigates the events in the vdir and, if necessary, updates the event date. Vdirsync will take care that everything is synched back to the CalDAV server. To deactivating, just remove the special marker from the subject. A piece of cake.

So thank you very much for vdir and vdirsync!

The code for the floating events is on GitHub: https://github.com/sciurius/vdirfloat .",{},{}
8684,IssuesEvent,2018-06-15 22:04:00+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,6504915,bmw,17889013,certbot,closed,Tweak output to not trigger markdown heading status,"[{'id': 200596079, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwyMDA1OTYwNzk=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/area:%20ui%20/%20ux', 'name': 'area: ui / ux', 'color': 'c5def5', 'default': False}, {'id': 276239890, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwyNzYyMzk4OTA=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/easy-fix', 'name': 'easy-fix', 'color': '207de5', 'default': False}, {'id': 149596829, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwxNDk1OTY4Mjk=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/good%20first%20issue', 'name': 'good first issue', 'color': 'c61aff', 'default': True}]",[],3,"We have a lot of horizontal lines of dashes in the Certbot output, e.g.

```
Which names would you like to activate HTTPS for?
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1: example.com
2: www.example.com
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
```

Unfortunately, Markdown interprets any text above one of these lines as a heading, leading to distracting and weird formatting when someone pastes it into the forum:

https://community.letsencrypt.org/t/certbot-apache-succeeded-now-site-times-out/63168/3

Arguably they should wrap things in triple-backticks, but this happens quite a lot: People who need help on the forum often don't take time to learn about Markdown. It would be nice to make a small tweak so that formatting just works correctly. Unfortunately, lines of underscores, plus signs, colons, or equal signs all have the same effect. One simple tweak that works is inserting a space (or multiple spaces) in the line of hyphens:

    - -------------------------------------------------------------------------------

or

    - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
",{},{}
