9227,IssuesEvent,2018-07-13 14:56:52+00:00,1380748,ninia/jep,5747885,ndjensen,28115331,ninia,closed,JEP doesn't build/install with Java >=10,"[{'id': 227719963, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwyMjc3MTk5NjM=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ninia/jep/labels/build', 'name': 'build', 'color': 'd4c5f9', 'default': False}]",[],5,"- OS Platform, Distribution, and Version: Ubuntu 18.04
- Python Distribution and Version: Python 3.6.5
- Java Distribution and Version: Oracle JDK 10

In, I believe, Java 8 Oracle added header-file-generation support to javac.  In JDK 9 javah was deprecated and in JDK 11 it was removed entirely [1].  This means that it isn't possible to build JEP under Oracle Java 10 or OpenJDK 10.  

In short header file generation should now be done using javac in conjunction with the ""-h <header_out_dir>"" option.  This has the side effect of compiling the referenced java classes.  The JEP should update its builder/installer to make use of the new JDK 8+ approach.  

[1] https://docs.oracle.com/javase/9/tools/javah.htm#JSWOR687

[jep_error.txt](https://github.com/ninia/jep/files/2028265/jep_error.txt)",{},{}
9238,IssuesEvent,2018-04-20 22:45:44+00:00,71948498,localstack/localstack,810894,djangofan,28732122,localstack,closed,Is there any need to use wait-for-it.sh with LocalStack?,[],[],2,"Is there any need to use wait-for-it.sh with LocalStack?   I have a test container that is marked with depends_on  localstack but  do I need to use a wait-for-it.sh  script  ( see https://docs.docker.com/compose/startup-order/ ) to wait for things like s3 or SQS to actually be ready?     I'm having trouble with a test-service not seeing a SQS queue and I suspect its because the SQS queue is not yet ready when the tests try to create the queue?

Better yet, is it possible there already is a custom wait for it script already in the localstack container that I can call?

I was thinking of something like this, but one that would check all services, not just s3:

```
#!/bin/bash
# wait-for-s3s.sh
# usage in docker-compose:
#  command: [""./wait-for-s3.sh""]

set -e

args=""$@""

until aws --region us-west-2 --no-sign-request --endpoint-url=http://localstack:4572 s3 mb s3://mytestbucket; do
  >&2 echo ""S3 is unavailable - sleeping""
  sleep 1
done

>&2 echo ""S3 is up - executing command""
exec aws --region us-west-2 --no-sign-request --endpoint-url=http://localstack:4572 s3 ls s3://mytestbucket;
```
",{},{}
